{"parse":{"title":"ade","pageid":576359,"redirects":[],"wikitext":"{{also|Appendix:Variations of \"ade\"}}\n==Translingual==\n\n===Symbol===\n{{mul-symbol}}\n\n# {{ISO 639|3}}\n\n===See also===\n* {{langcat}}\n\n==English==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{back-form|en|lemonade}}, {{m|en|orangeade}}, etc.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|en|/ˈeɪd/}}\n* {{audio|en|LL-Q1860 (eng)-Flame, not lame-ade.wav|a=US}}\n* {{rhymes|en|eɪd|s=1}}\n* {{homophone|en|aid|aide}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{en-noun}}\n\n# A [[drink]] made from a [[fruit]], especially a [[fizzy]] one.\n#: {{syn|en|fruitade}}\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=1895|author=John G Bourke|title=Folk-foods of the Rio Grande Valley of Northern Mexico|page=61|passage=To come to the tables or stands: they were loaded with chocolate, coffee, agua de miel, pulque, mescal, orchatas of several kinds, all the lemon and other \"'''ades'''\" already described, as well as all the cakes and candies, {{...}}}}\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=1905|title=American Bottler|volume=25|page=74\n|passage=If the judgment of the above-mentioned office be correct, in truth, no drink may here be offered to the public as lemonade unless it is made out of fresh fruit! And so with raspberryade and all the other \"'''ades'''.\"}}\n\n====Derived terms====\n{{col|en|grapefruitade}}\n\n====Translations====\n{{trans-top|drink made from a fruit}}\n* Chinese:\n*: Mandarin: {{t+|cmn|泡泡|tr=pàopào}}, {{t+|cmn|果汁|tr=guǒzhī}}\n* Dutch: {{t+|nl|limonade|f}}, {{t+|nl|priklimonade|f}}, {{t+|nl|frisdrank|m}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|limu}} {{q|fizzy}}; {{t|fi|hedelmäjuoma}}\n* Japanese: {{t|ja|エード|tr=ēdo}}\n* Korean: {{t|ko|에이드}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n===Anagrams===\n* {{anagrams|en|a=ade|Eda|'ead|DAE|EAD|DEA|EDA|AED}}\n\n{{topics|en|Beverages}}\n\n==Bangka==\n\n===Alternative forms===\n* {{alt|mfb|ado<qq:Belinyu dialect>}}\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{inh|mfb|poz-mly-pro|*ada(ʔ)}}, from {{der|mfb|poz-pro|*wada}}. Cognate of {{cog|ms|ada}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|mfb|/ˈade/|/ˈadə/}}\n\n===Verb===\n{{head|mfb|v|head=adè|head2=adê}}\n\n# to [[be]] {{gloss|exist}}\n#: {{ant|mfb|dakde}}\n#: {{usex|mfb|'''Ade''' due telok ayam.|'''There are''' two chicken eggs.}}\n# to [[have]]\n#: {{syn|mfb|punye}}\n#: {{ant|mfb|dakde|dak}}\n#: {{usex|mfb|Aku '''ade''' buku baru|I '''have''' a new book.}}\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{R:mfb:Susilo 2018}}\n\n==Esperanto==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{etymon|eo|:af|-ad-|-e}}\nFrom {{suffix|eo|-ad-|-e}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n{{eo-pr|a=LL-Q143 (epo)-Lepticed7-ade.wav;LL-Q143 (epo)-Robin van der Vliet-ade.wav}}\n\n===Adverb===\n{{eo-head}}\n\n# [[continually]], [[permanently]], [[consistently]]\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{R:eo:PIV 2020}}\n\n==Ewe==\n{{number box|ee}}\n\n===Etymology===\n{{rfe|ee}}\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{ee-IPA|àdé}}\n\n===Numeral===\n{{ee-number|àdé}}\n\n# [[six]]\n\n===References===\n* {{R:ee:Basic Ewe|19}}\n* {{R:ee:Nuseline|7}}\n\n==Garo==\n\n===Etymology===\nClipping of {{l|grt|ma·de}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|grt|noun}}\n\n# [[younger]] [[maternal aunt]]\n\n====Synonyms====\n* {{l|grt|ma·degipa}} {{qualifier|formal}}\n* {{l|grt|ma·detang}} {{qualifier|formal}}\n* {{l|grt|ma·de}}\n\n{{C|grt|Female family members}}\n\n==German==\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{inh|de|gmh|adē}}, from {{der|de|fro|adieu}}. {{doublet|de|tschö}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|de|/aˈdeː/}}\n* {{rhymes|de|eː|s=2}}\n* {{audio|de|De-Ade.ogg}}\n* {{audio|de|De-ade.ogg|a=<<Germany>> (<<Berlin>>)}}\n\n===Interjection===\n{{head|de|interjection}}\n\n# {{lb|de|archaic|poetic|or|regional}} [[farewell]], [[adieu]]\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{R:de:Duden}}\n* {{R:de:DWDS}}\n\n{{cln|de|farewells}}\n\n==Guanche==\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|gnc|noun}}\n\n# [[water]]\n\n===References===\n* Juan Álvarez Delgado, ''Miscelánea guanche : I. Benahoare : ensayos de lingüística canaria'', 1942\n\n==Lindu==\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|klw|noun}}\n\n# {{lb|klw|anatomy}} [[chin]]\n\n==Macanese==\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{der|mzs|roa-opt|ãade|t=duck; mallard}}, possibly via a de-nasalized variant of {{der|mzs|pt|adem|t=mallard}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|mzs|/ˈa.di/}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|mzs|noun}}\n\n# [[duck]]\n#: {{coi|mzs|'''ade''' salgado|t='''duck''' salted in brine}}\n#: {{coi|mzs|'''ade'''-cabidela|t=''stew made with duck and duck blood''}}\n#: {{coi|mzs|voz di '''ade'''-macho|t=hoarse/husky voice|lit=voice of male '''duck'''}}\n\n====Usage notes====\n* Macanese makes a distinction between {{m|mzs|ade|t=duck}} and {{m|mzs|pato|t=drake}}. This distinction is obsolete in Portugal.\n\n====Derived terms====\n* {{l|mzs|bafo di ade}}\n\n===References===\n* https://www.macaneselibrary.org/pub/english/uipatua.htm#ade\n* https://www.macaneselibrary.org/pub/english/uipatua.htm#f_ade\n\n{{C|mzs|Ducks|Poultry}}\n\n==Northern Kurdish==\n\n===Etymology 1===\n{{rfe|kmr}}\n\n====Alternative forms====\n* {{alter|kmr|ede|'ede|ادا}}\n\n====Pronunciation====\n* {{kmr-IPA}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{kmr-noun|m|ar=ئادە}}\n\n# [[weed]] {{gl|unwanted plant}}\n\n=====Declension=====\n{{kmr-decl-noun|m}}\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n* {{l|kmr|ade kirin}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\n\n====Pronunciation====\n* {{kmr-IPA}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{kmr-noun|f|ar=ئادە}}\n\n# {{altform|kmr|ada|t=island}}\n\n=====Declension=====\n{{kmr-decl-noun|f}}\n\n===References===\n* {{R:kmr:Chyet:2020|ada I|vol=1|page=1}}\n* {{R:kmr:Chyet:2020|ada II|vol=1|page=2}}\n\n{{C|kmr|Plants}}\n\n==Wiwa==\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|mbp|noun}}\n\n# [[father]]\n#: ranže ade terga\n#:: my father is in the field\n\n===References===\n* ''The Languages of the Andes'' (2004, Willem F. H. Adelaar, Pieter C. Muysken)<!--citing Trillos Amaya 2000)-->\n\n==Wolio==\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{inh|wlo|poz-pro|*qazay}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|wlo|/aɗe/}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|wlo|noun}}\n\n# [[chin]]\n\n===References===\n* Anceaux, Johannes C. 1987. ''Wolio Dictionary (Wolio-English-Indonesian) / Kamus Bahasa Wolio (Wolio-Inggeris-Indonesia).'' Dordrecht: Foris.\n\n==Yoruba==\n[[File:Brooklyn Museum 70.109.1a-b Beaded Crown Ade of Onijagbo Obasoro Alowolodu Ogoga of Ikere 1890-1928 (2).jpg|thumb|'''Adé''' láti Ikẹ́rẹ́]]\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{affix|yo|a-|dé|t1=agent prefix|id1=agent prefix|t2=to wear on the head, to cap, to crown|lit=that which is worn on the head}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{yo-IPA|adé}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{yo-noun|adé}}\n\n# [[crown]]\n# {{lb|yo|by extension}} [[royalty]]\n# A [[common]] [[prefix]] in Yoruba [[given]] [[names]] and [[surnames]] for those born in [[royalty]]\n# the [[top]] [[part]] of [[something]]\n## the [[top]] [[part]] of a [[tree]]\n\n====Derived terms====\n{{col2|yo\n|aládé<t:prince, princess, royal>\n|Adébáyọ̀<pos:Yoruba name><lit:Royalty meets joy>\n|Adéyanjú<pos:Yoruba name><lit:The crown is complete>\n|Adéṣidà<pos:Yoruba name><lit:The crown has not broken any taboos>\n|Adébọ́rọ̀<pos:Yoruba name><lit:Royalty meets wealth>\n}}\n\n==Zaghawa==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|zag|/ʔadɛ/}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|zag|noun}}\n\n# [[beard]]\n\n===References===\n* ''[https://web.archive.org/web/20230314181521/http://www.tchad.org/zaghawa/Beria-Eng-BDict.pdf Beria-English English-Beria Dictionary] [provisional] ADESK, Iriba, Kobe Department, Chad''"}}